Background Research:¶

Natural Language Processing (NLP) involves the interaction between computers and human language. A common task in NLP is text generation, where the objective is to create human-like text. This capability finds applications in diverse fields, including chatbots, content generation, and machine translation.

In the realm of text generation, the challenge arises when aiming to produce contextually relevant and coherent sentences. Addressing this challenge is crucial for the successful implementation of various NLP applications.

In this context, quotes text generation is the specific focus. The model is trained to generate text resembling a given set of quotes, providing a unique approach to creating meaningful and contextually appropriate content.

# Plot the training and validation accuracy and loss at each epoch
def plot_history(history, epochs):
    """
        This function plots the training and validation accuracy and loss at each epoch

        Parameters:
            model (keras.models): Keras model
            history (keras.callbacks.History): History object
            epochs (int): Number of epochs
            test_data (tf.data.Dataset): Test data
    """
    sns.set_context('notebook',  font_scale=1.2)
    sns.set_style('whitegrid', {'grid.color': '0.9'})

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 8))

    ax = ax.ravel()

    for i, metric in enumerate(['accuracy', 'loss']):
        ax[i].plot(range(epochs), history.history[metric])
        ax[i].plot(range(epochs), history.history['val_' + metric])
        ax[i].set_title(f"Model {metric}")
        ax[i].set_xlabel("Epochs")
        ax[i].set_ylabel(metric)
        ax[i].legend(['train', 'val'])
    
    # Set y ticks for plot
    ax[0].set_yticks(list(map(lambda x: round(x, ndigits=2), np.linspace(0, 1, 11).tolist())))
    ax[1].set_yticks(list(map(lambda x: round(x, ndigits=2), np.linspace(0, 5, 11).tolist())))

Let us take a look at the word cloud of the dataset

Observations:

  • We can see how the most common words are both a mix of starting words which are capitalized (e.g. Embrace, Dance, Life, Believe, Radiate) as well as other words in the quote (e.g. will, let, morning, heart, planet etc.)

Now, let's analyse the different common n-grams

In [ ]:
# Do subplot of n-grams
from nltk import ngrams
from collections import Counter

fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 1, figsize=(16, 8))

# Convert data to string
data_str = ' '.join(data)

grams_count = [2, 3, 4]

for i, gram in enumerate(grams_count):
    # Create n-grams
    n_grams = ngrams(data_str.split(), gram)
    n_grams_freq = Counter(n_grams)
    most_common_n_grams = n_grams_freq.most_common(10)

    # Convert keys of most_common_n_grams to string
    most_common_n_grams = list(map(lambda x: ' '.join(x[0]), most_common_n_grams))
    
    # Plot the most common n-grams
    sns.barplot(x=most_common_n_grams, y=list(map(lambda x: x[1], n_grams_freq.most_common(10))), ax=ax[i], palette='Blues_d', hue=most_common_n_grams)
    ax[i].set_xticks(range(10))
    ax[i].set_xticklabels(most_common_n_grams, rotation=10, fontfamily='serif', fontsize=10)
    ax[i].set_ylabel('Count', fontsize=15)
    ax[i].set_title(f"Most common {gram}-grams", fontfamily='serif', fontsize=14)

fig.suptitle("Most common n-grams", fontsize=20, fontfamily='serif')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observations:

  • For 2-gram, it shows that the top two most common 2-grams are "is a" and "be the". However, notice how it is very hard to spot these words inside the word cloud. This shows that the common 2-grams and 1-grams are actually quite different
  • For the top three 4-grams, we can see how it is similar to the top three 3-grams with only addition of one extra word. This means that most phrases in the quotes are only similar up to 3-grams

ax.annotate(f"Max: {max(data_str)}", xy=(max(data_str), 0), xytext=(max(data_str)-1, 180), arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.05), fontfamily='serif')

ax.set_title("Number of words in each quote", fontsize=20, fontfamily='serif')

plt.show()

Observations:

  • The minimum number of quotes in the dataset is 7 and the maximum number of quotes is 35. This is important as it means that later on when generating input output pairs, we can only generate a maximum of uptil 7
  • From the histogram, we can see that the distribution of the number of words is positively-skewed with the mode at around 11 quotes
  • However, there are quite a lot of outliers with some quotes having more than 20 words

Feature Engineering¶

First let us start off by tokenizing our words. We will be using Word Tokenization to Tokenize our text. In word tokenization, the data is split up into words and each unique word is tokenized with a unique index.

We will be implmeneting this in tensorflow, where by default, tensorflow has its own stop words which will be filtered out of our dataset

Creating input-output pairings¶

For the generation of input-output pairings, we will be borrowing some concepts from time series, namely:

  1. Expanding Window
  2. Rolling Window (Sliding Window)

Method 1: Expanding Window

In expanding window, the window size changes with each prediction. So if the initial window size is n, the first prediction would use n days of data, the second prediction will use n+1 days of data and the $k^{th}$ day will use n+k days of data

Method 2: Rolling Window

For rolling window, the window size remains constant with each prediction but it shifts to the right by one. So if the initial window size is n, the first prediction would use data from [1, n], the second prediction will use data from [2, n+1] and the $k^{th}$ data will use data from [k, n+k-1]

Relevance to input output pair generation

Similar to how expanding window and rolling window are used in time series, we can use them to generate input output pairs since they are both sequences. In this case, the training data will be the input and the forecasted data will be the output. However, the forecasted data will only be forecasting one word into the future

E.g: Given the sequence "Who controls the past controls the future.", Input Output


Expanding Window

=> Using a window size of 1 (i.e. 1-gram)

Pass 1: Who controls the past controls the future.

Pass 2: Who controls the past controls the future.

Pass 3: Who controls the past controls the future.

Pass 4: Who controls the past controls the future.

and so on

after that, we can even go on and restart again but this time start from the second word

i.e.

Pass 1: Who controls the past controls the future.

Pass 2: Who controls the past controls the future.

Pass 3: Who controls the past controls the future.

etc. until we reach the very end


Rolling Window

=> Using a window size of n (i.e. n-gram)

For one gram,

Pass 1: Who controls the past controls the future.

Pass 2: Who controls the past controls the future.

Pass 3: Who controls the past controls the future.

Pass 4: Who controls the past controls the future.

For two gram,

Pass 1: Who controls the past controls the future.

Pass 2: Who controls the past controls the future.

Pass 3: Who controls the past controls the future.


Notice how when generating pairs with both methods simultaneously, we will inevitably end up with duplicated input output pairs

Using the Expanding Window Strategy

Using a nested for loop, we can generate input output pairs using the expanding window strategy

def create_ngrams(input_sequence=input_sequence, ngrams=2):
    n_grams = []
    for datapoint in input_sequence:
        for i in range(len(datapoint) - ngrams):
            n_grams.append(datapoint[i:i+ngrams])
    return n_grams

Model Training¶

Baseline Model (Vanilla RNN)¶

RNN Layers Explained

Let us start off by building a vanilla RNN model. RNNs (Recurrent neural networks), are used to handle the shortcomings that feedfoward neural networks have when dealing with sequetial data

The pros and cons of a Vanilla RNN compared to a Feed Foward Network is summed up below:

Advantages Disadvantages
Possibility of processing input of any length Computation is much slower
Computation takes into account historical information Difficult to access information from a long time ago

Figure: Feed Forward Network vs RNN

Unlike how Feed Forward Networks are unidirectional, RNN's has loops inside it to persist information over the sequence. $h_t$ is the hidden state of the input at time $t$.

During every forward propagation, there is a recurrence relation applied where the current hidden state is calculated based on the previous hidden state and the input at the current through $h_t = f_w(W_{hh}^{t}h_{t-1} + W_{xh}^{t}X_{t})$ where $f_w$ is a non-linear function like $tanh$. The hidden state can be considered the "memory" of the network

At evey cell, $\hat{y_t}$ denotes the output at step $t$ and it can be calculated using the current hidden state $\hat{y_t} = softmax(W_{hy}^{t}h_t)$

Note that when calculating the current hidden state, tanh is used and when calculating the output, softmax is used. This is because relu is usually avoided (unless gradient clipping is used) due to the exploding gradient problem and a non-linear function is needed to calculate the current hidden state so tanh is used to calculate the the current hidden state to resize the input values to the range of [-1, 1]. Howver, when trying to convert the raw output scores into a probability distribution, softmax has to be used which is why it is used to calculate the output

Figure: Image of a single Vanilla RNN Cell

Vanilla RNN Baseline Model Architecture

  1. Embedding => Used to turn positive integers into dense vectors of fixed size
  • Input dimension: 1119 (vocabulary size)
  • Output dimension: 100
  • Input Length: 34 (input sequence length)
  1. Simple RNN
  • Number of Cells: 64
  • Activation Function: 'tanh'
  • Dropout: 0.3
  1. Output Layer
  • Neurons: 1119 (vocabulary size)
  • Activation Function: 'softmax'

Optimizer: Adam Epochs: 30

In [ ]:
# Input is max sequence length - 1, as we've removed the last word for the label.
input_len = max_sequence_len - 1 

RNN_model = Sequential(
    name='VanillaRNN_model',
    layers=[
        Embedding(total_words, 100, input_length=input_len),
        SimpleRNN(64, activation = 'tanh', dropout=0.3),
        Dense(total_words, activation='softmax')
    ]
)

RNN_model.summary()

RNN_model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.005), metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train the model.
RNN_history = RNN_model.fit(train_ds.batch(64), validation_data=val_ds.batch(64), epochs=30, verbose=1)

In [ ]:
def predict_next_N_words(input_text, N=10, model=RNN_model):
    for _ in range(N):
        # Tokenize the input text
        token_list = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences([input_text])[0]
        # Pad the input text
        token_list = pad_sequences([token_list], maxlen=max_sequence_len-1, padding='pre')
        # Predict the next word
        predicted_prob = model.predict(token_list, verbose=0)[0]
        chosen_word_index = np.argmax(predicted_prob)
        # Convert the predicted word to text
        predicted_word = tokenizer.index_word[chosen_word_index]
        input_text += " " + predicted_word
    return input_text

LSTM and GRU¶

In order to remedy the vanishing gradient problem, specific gates are used in some types of RNNs with each gate having a well-defined purpose. They can be combuted using $\Gamma = \sigma(Wx^{t} + Uh^{t-1} + b)$, where $W$, $U$ and $b$ are coefficients specific to the gate and $\sigma$ is the sigmoid function. The main gates are:

Type of gate Role Used In
Update gate $\Gamma_{u}$ How much past should matter now? GRU, LSTM
Relevance gate $\Gamma_{r}$ Drop previous information? GRU, LSTM
Forget gate $\Gamma_{f}$ Erase a cell or not? LSTM
Output gate $\Gamma_{o}$ How much to reveal of a cell? LSTM

Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU)

Figure: Image of GRU Cell

A GRU has two gates, a reset gate $\Gamma_{r}$ and an update gate $\Gamma_{u}$

The reset gate determines how to combine the new input with the previous memory and update gates defines how much of the previous memory to keep around

In [ ]:
# Input is max sequence length - 1, as we've removed the last word for the label.
input_len = max_sequence_len - 1 

GRU_model = Sequential(
    name='GRU_model',
    layers=[
        Embedding(total_words, 100, input_length=input_len),
        GRU(128, activation = 'tanh', dropout=0.3, recurrent_regularizer=l2(0.001)),
        Dense(total_words, activation='softmax')
    ]
)

GRU_model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.005), metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train the model.

Long Short Term Memory (LSTM)

Figure: Image of LSTM Cell

The idea behind a LSTM layer is quite similar to a GRU layer. However, LSTM has more gates than GRU and can typically capture longer dependencies compared to GRU.

LSTM also introduces the concept of a memory cell $C_{i}$ (a numerical vector of pre-defined size) which is updated each time a new input is supplied

It also has two additional gates, the forget gate $\Gamma_{f}$ which is used to control how much past memory is kept from the previous hidden state $h_{t-1}$ and the current input $X_t$ and the output gate $\Gamma_{o}$ which is used to update the hidden state

Temperature

Let us now compare the difference in text prediction for LSTM and GRU

Notice how previously, our implementation of predict_next_N_words would always give the same results when given the same seed texts. In order to make our model capable of producing different sequences of output texts given the same input, we can introduce a new parameter called temperature

Temperature is often used to control the randomness of the output distribution. Typically a higher temperature increases the amount of randomness which can lead to more diverse outputs while a lower temperature decreases the amount of randomness which leads to more deterministic outputs. Temperature is often used to adjust the distribution of probabilities generated by the softmax function and can be calculated as follows

$$\sigma(z_{i}) = \frac{e^{\frac{z_{i}}{T}}}{\Sigma_{k=0}^{N}e^{\frac{z_{k}}{T}}}$$

In summary, higher temperatures make the model more "creative" while lower temperatures can make the model more confident and provide more "meaningful" answers

In [ ]:
def predict_next_N_words(input_text, N=10, temperature=0.1, model=RNN_model):
    for _ in range(N):
        # Tokenize the input text
        token_list = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences([input_text])[0]
        # Pad the input text
        token_list = pad_sequences([token_list], maxlen=max_sequence_len-1, padding='pre')
        # Predict the next word
        predicted_prob = model.predict(token_list, verbose=0)[0]
        # Apply temperature
        predicted_prob = np.array(predicted_prob)**(1/temperature)
        predicted_prob = predicted_prob / np.sum(predicted_prob)
        chosen_word_index = np.random.choice(len(predicted_prob), p=predicted_prob)
        # Convert the predicted word to text
        predicted_word = tokenizer.index_word[chosen_word_index]
        input_text += " " + predicted_word
    return input_text

Bidirectional Models¶

Figure: Image of an Bidirectional Model

Bidirectional models are architectures that process data in both forward and backward directions which allows the model to capture information from the past and the future context of each input which is useful in tasks where understanding context is important.

Bidirectional LTSM

Instead of using a unidirectional LSTM, we could use a Bidirectional wrapper around the LSTM layer which processes the input sequence in both the forward and backward directions creating two sets of hidden states: one capturing informatino from the past and the other from the future.

In [ ]:
# Bidirectional LSTM

# Input is max sequence length - 1, as we've removed the last word for the label.
input_len = max_sequence_len - 1

BiLSTM_model = Sequential(
    name='Bidirectional_LSTM_model',
    layers=[
        Embedding(total_words, 100, input_length=input_len),
        Bidirectional(LSTM(128, activation = 'tanh')),
        Dense(total_words, activation='softmax')
    ]
)

BiLSTM_model.summary()

BiLSTM_model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.005), metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train the model.
BiLSTM_history = BiLSTM_model.fit(train_ds.batch(64), validation_data=val_ds.batch(64), epochs=30, verbose=1)

Decoding Methods

So far, we have only been using the greedy method for decoding, however, there are many other methods such as:

  • Beam Search
  • K-sampling
  • Neucleus-sampling

We will be using a few of them to try and make our model text output more creative

Greedy Search

So far, the only method we have been using is greedy search.

Greedy search selects from the language model the word with the highest probability as the next word.

Figure: Greedy Search diagram

Suppose the language model is predicting a possible continuation to a sentence starting with "The", then by using greedy search, the model will always choose the word with the highest probability which in this case, is "cat". In our implementation of predict_next_N_words, we used temperature to introduce some randomness to greedy search. However, there are other alternatives to try and get different texts or more creative outputs

Top-K-Sampling

In Top-K sampling, the top K words with the highest words are filtered and then the next predicted word will be randomly sampled among these K words. The produced text from Top-K sampling can be more human-sounding than the text produced with Greedy Search. However, one concern with Top-K sampling is that it does not dynamically adapt the number of words that are filtered as K is fixed. As a consequence, very unlikely words may be selected among these K words if the next word probability distribution is very sharp

Nucleus (Top-p) sampling

Nucleus sampling chooses from the smallest possible set of words whose cumulative probability exceeds the probability p. THis way, the number of words in the set can dynamically increase and decrease according to the next word probability distribution

In [ ]:
def greedy(input_text, temperature=0.1, N=10, model=RNN_model):
    log_likelihood = 0
    for _ in range(N):
        # Tokenize the input text
        token_list = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences([input_text])[0]
        # Pad the input text
        token_list = pad_sequences([token_list], maxlen=max_sequence_len-1, padding='pre')
        # Predict the next word
        predicted_prob = model.predict(token_list, verbose=0)[0]
        np.seterr(divide = 'ignore')
        predictions = np.log(predicted_prob) / (temperature)
        np.seterr(divide = 'warn')
        exp_predictions = np.exp(predictions)
        predicted_probs = exp_predictions / np.sum(exp_predictions)
        chosen_word_index = np.random.choice(range(len(predicted_probs)), p=predicted_probs)
        # Convert the predicted word to text
        predicted_word = tokenizer.index_word[chosen_word_index]
        input_text += " " + predicted_word
        log_likelihood += np.log2(predicted_prob[chosen_word_index])
    return input_text, log_likelihood

def k_sampling(input_text, k=75, temperature=0.1, N=10, model=RNN_model):
    log_likelihood = 0
    for _ in range(N):
        # Tokenize the input text
        token_list = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences([input_text])[0]
        # Pad the input text
        token_list = pad_sequences([token_list], maxlen=max_sequence_len-1, padding='pre')
        # Predict the next word
        predicted_prob = model.predict(token_list, verbose=0)[0]
        predicted_prob = np.array(predicted_prob)
        # Reduce those not in top k to 0 (i.e. filter out those not in top k)
        predicted_prob[np.argsort(predicted_prob)[:-k]] = 0
        np.seterr(divide = 'ignore')
        predictions = np.log(predicted_prob) / temperature
        np.seterr(divide = 'warn')
        exp_predictions = np.exp(predictions)
        predicted_probs = exp_predictions / np.sum(exp_predictions)
        # Random sample from top k
        chosen_word_index = np.random.choice(range(len(predicted_probs)), p=predicted_probs)
        # Convert the predicted word to text
        predicted_word = tokenizer.index_word[chosen_word_index]
        input_text += " " + predicted_word
        log_likelihood += np.log2(predicted_prob[chosen_word_index])
    return input_text, log_likelihood

# Predict the nucleus top p sampling
def nucleus_sampling(input_text, p=0.5, temperature=0.1, N=10, model=RNN_model):
    log_likelihood = 0
    for _ in range(N):
        # Tokenize the input text
        token_list = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences([input_text])[0]
        # Pad the input text
        token_list = pad_sequences([token_list], maxlen=max_sequence_len-1, padding='pre')
        # Predict the next word
        predicted_prob = model.predict(token_list, verbose=0)[0]
        predicted_prob = np.array(predicted_prob)
        # Reduce those not in top p to 0 (i.e. filter out those not in top p)
        sorted_probs = np.sort(predicted_prob)
        sorted_probs = sorted_probs[::-1]
        sorted_probs = sorted_probs.cumsum()
        sorted_probs /= sorted_probs[-1]
        # Get indices of those in top p
        indices = np.arange(len(sorted_probs))
        selected_indices = indices[sorted_probs <= p]
        # Reduce those not in top p to 0
        predicted_prob[selected_indices] = 0
        np.seterr(divide = 'ignore')
        predictions = np.log(predicted_prob) / temperature
        np.seterr(divide = 'warn')
        exp_predictions = np.exp(predictions)
        predicted_probs = exp_predictions / np.sum(exp_predictions)
        # Random sample from top p
        chosen_word_index = np.random.choice(range(len(predicted_probs)), p=predicted_probs)
        # Convert the predicted word to text
        predicted_word = tokenizer.index_word[chosen_word_index]
        input_text += " " + predicted_word
        log_likelihood += np.log2(predicted_prob[chosen_word_index])
    return input_text, log_likelihood

Attention layer¶

Attention mechanisms enhance deep learning models by selectively focusing on important input elements which improves prediction accuracy. They emphasize on relevant information acting as a spotlight to enhance overall model performance

The attention mechanism works by assigning a weight to each part of the input sequence. The model then uses these weights to calculate a weighted sum of the input sequence which is used to generate the output sequence. The parts of the input sequence which are more important are given higher weights so they have a greater influence on the output sequence

Since our LSTM Model did seem to perform better compared to the Bi-directional LSTM model, we wll be using LSTM instead of Bi-directional LSTM for our model with attention

In [ ]:
# Attention is all you need

# Input is max sequence length - 1, as we've removed the last word for the label.
input_len = max_sequence_len - 1

inputs = Input(shape=(input_len,))
embedding_layer = Embedding(total_words, 100, input_length=input_len)(inputs)
attention_in = LSTM(256, return_sequences=True, recurrent_regularizer=l2(0.001), dropout=0.3)(embedding_layer)

# Add attention
attention = Attention(use_scale=True)([attention_in, attention_in])
# Return last output instead of entire sequence
outputs = TimeDistributed(Dense(total_words, activation='softmax'))(attention)
reshape_outputs = Lambda(lambda x: x[:, -1, :])(outputs)


LSTMAttention_model = Model(inputs, reshape_outputs, name='LSTMAttention_model')

LSTMAttention_model.summary()

LSTMAttention_model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.005), metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train the model.
LSTMAttention_history = LSTMAttention_model.fit(train_ds.batch(64), validation_data=val_ds.batch(64), epochs=30, verbose=1)

Previously, we have always been manually trying to evaluate the text generated from our model. However, it is quite obvious that manually evaluating text is quite subjective as it is not a process with pre-defined steps. In addition, it can also start to become time-consuming if our seed_texts becomes longer.

As such, we can go ahead and use some of the common metrics use to evaluate text generation to try and provide a more objective and quantifiable measure for the model's performance

  1. Bleu Score

Bleu Score, which stands for Bilingual Evaluation Understudy Score, is a metric used for evaluating a generated sentence compared to a reference sentence. It calculates the n-gram overlap of the reference and generated texts. The score is calculated using the geometric mean of the precision for n-grams in the generated text that match with the reference text such that more overlaps will result in a higher Bleu Score. The score ranges from [0, 1] with 1 being the best possible score

  1. Perplexity

Perplexity is a measure of how well a probability model predicts a sample. In the context of Natural Language Processing (NLP), it is used as a measure of probability for a sentence to be produced by the model trained on a dataset.

The perplexity of a discrete probability distribution is defined as: $$ Perplexity = 2^{H(p)} = 2^{-\Sigma_{x}p(x)log_{2}p(x)}$$

where H(p) is the entropy of the distribution p(x) and x is a random variable over all possible events

We can futher simplify the equation as follows:

$$ \begin{align} Perplexity &= 2^{-\Sigma_{x}^{N}p(x)log_{2}q(x)} \nonumber \\ &= 2^{-\Sigma_{x}^{N}\frac{1}{N}log_{2}q(x)} \text{(assuming all words have the same frequency)} \nonumber \\ \end{align} $$

where p is the probability distribution that we want to model and q is our proposed probability model (i.e. our prediction) By using q and testing it against samples drawn from p, we are basically calculating the cross-entropy so we can use the probability array generated when predicting the next word and use it for q(x) to manually calculate perplexity

Figure: Image of perplexity calculation

# Used for evaluation of the model
from nltk.translate.bleu_score import corpus_bleu, SmoothingFunction

# Smoothing function made by chencherry
chencherry = SmoothingFunction()

def evaluate_bleu(references, text):

    candidate = ["".join([text]).split(" ")]

    score = corpus_bleu(references, candidate, weights=(0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.4), smoothing_function=chencherry.method1)
    return score

def evaluate_perplexity(log_likelihood, num_words):
    
    perplexity = 2**(-log_likelihood / num_words)
    
    return perplexity

    refHeader = ['Embrace', 'Radiate', 'Believe in yourself', "Life's", "Dance through", "Let your", "Every", "Singapore" ,"Our planet", "This morning, let"]

    # Used to filter out and only get specific quotes
    if type(refType) == int and 0 <= refType < len(refHeader):
        refHeader = [refHeader[refType]]
    # Invalid refType
    elif refType != 'all':
        print("Invalid refType")
        return
    
    ref = []
    for quote in data:
        for substring in refHeader:
            if (substring in quote):
                ref += [re.sub('[,;.]', '', quote).split(" ")]

    return [ref]

Model Evaluation¶

Let us now evaluate all the models we have trained so far and get their mean BLEU scores, loss and perplexity.

In [ ]:
eval_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model', 'Mean Greedy BLEU', 'Mean Greedy Perplexity', 'Mean K-Sampling BLEU', 'Mean K-Sampling Perplexity', 'Mean Nucleus Sampling BLEU', 'Mean Nucleus Sampling Perplexity'])
models = [RNN_model, GRU_model, LSTM_model, BiLSTM_model, LSTMAttention_model]
decoders = [greedy, k_sampling, nucleus_sampling]

for model in models:
    model_eval = []
    for decoder in decoders:
        bleu = 0
        perplexity = 0
        for i, text in enumerate(seed_texts):
            references = getReferences('all')
            prediction, loss = decoder(text, temperature=0.3, model=model)
            bleu += evaluate_bleu(references, prediction)
            perplexity += evaluate_perplexity(loss, len(prediction.split(" ")))
        avg_bleu = bleu/len(seed_texts)
        avg_perplexity = perplexity/len(seed_texts)
        # Add to list
        model_eval += [avg_bleu, avg_perplexity]
    # Add to eval_df
    eval_df.loc[len(eval_df)] = [model.name] + model_eval

display(eval_df)

Observations:

  • Using different decoding methods for different models, we can see how Bidirectional LSTM tend to have the worst BLEU scores compared to the rest of the models which suggests that most of its predicted text is quite different from the reference text
  • The Mean Perplexity for GRU seems to be consistently one of the lowest which suggests that the model is quite confident with its prediction
  • However, in general, the models BLEU scores and Perplexity are all quite close to one another which suggests that there is not much difference in terms of these evaluation metrics even though the predicted texts may be very different
  • As such, this also shows why there is a lack of standard evaluation metrics used for evaluating text generation because this shows how it is hard to evaluate the model's performance using metrics such as BLEU and Perplexity since both metrics actually do not consider
    1. The order of words
    2. The meaning of words
    3. The importance of words

Now let us take a look at the effects of temperature on the different metrics. In this case, we will be using the extreme examples of temperature 0.1 and 0.9 to best illustrate the point

In [ ]:
temperature_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model', '0.1 BLEU', '0.1 Perplexity', '0.9 BLEU', '0.9 Perplexity'])

models = [RNN_model, GRU_model, LSTM_model, BiLSTM_model, LSTMAttention_model]
temperature = [0.1, 0.9]

for model in models:
    model_eval = []
    for temp in temperature:
        bleu = 0
        perplexity = 0
        for i, text in enumerate(seed_texts):
            references = getReferences('all')
            prediction, loss = greedy(text, temperature=temp, model=model)
            bleu += evaluate_bleu(references, prediction)
            perplexity += evaluate_perplexity(loss, len(prediction.split(" ")))
        avg_bleu = bleu/len(seed_texts)
        avg_perplexity = perplexity/len(seed_texts)
        # Add to list
        model_eval += [avg_bleu, avg_perplexity]
    # Add to temperature_df
    temperature_df.loc[len(temperature_df)] = [model.name] + model_eval

Observations:

  • When using a lower temperature of 0.1, the BLEU score is typically higher compared to when using a higher temperature of 0.9 for all the models. This is because with a lower temperature, there has a lower amount of randomness so the predicted output will be more similar to the reference text making it more meaningful while with a higher temperature, there is more randomness introduced so the predicted output will be mroe different from the refrence text making it more creative since it is different
  • As such, this shows that BLEU score can actually be used as a metric to evaluate how the given the predicted text, whether it is considered more meaningful or more creative
  • When using a lower temperature of 0.1, the preplexity is typically lower compared to when using a higher temperature of 0.9 for all the models. This is because due to the lower amount of randomness introduced, the model is more confident of its predicted word so the loss of each predicteed word will be lower

Final Thoughts on the model improvement process:

In this assignment, I tried to slowly improve the quality of the generated text through a variety of methods: using different models (LSTM, GRU, Bi-directional models), trying out different decoding methods, using an attention layer etc. From a metrics point of view, there is quite a substantial improvement when comparing the accuracy and loss used during training as well as the Bleu score and Perplexity for the text generated with our final LSTM attention model (with the LSTM Attention model consistently having the highest Bleu score and one of the lowest perplexity for different decoding methods and temperature values) which should indicate a better quality of generated text.

However, the truth is that the general text generated for the model is still quite incoherent. Although there are some seed texts such as 'Radiate'and 'Embrace' which the model tend to perform well and give coherent and meaningful sentences at, there are also other seed texts such as 'morning and evening would make it', 'dance through each and every' 'believe that' that all the models consistently perform poorly at with no sign of improvement after trying out the different methods.

The poor performance in text generation coupled with the fact that the training and validation accuracy during the model training are almost identical indicates that there is simply not sufficient data for the model to extract as seen by how the Bi-directional LSTM ended up performing worse compared to LSTM simply because of the short sequence length in the dataset

Due to some of the constraints in this assignment, some of these techniques were not implemented. However, all is not lost as there are still a few techniques that can help improve the model's performance:

  • Vector Embedding: Instead of using word tokenization where every word in the vocabulary gets a unique token, an alternative could be to try out vector embedding where each word is instead represented as a vector which can contain the association between words (and the semantic similarity of two words can be measured using the cosine similarity of their vectors)
  • Larger dataset: A dataset with only 1000 quotes is definitely not sufficient for the training of the model. Coupled with the fact that 10% (110) of the quotes are actually duplicates, we only end up with 890 quotes to work with for the training of our model. RNN models, like other deep learning models, require large amounts of data to learn effectively. A small dataset might not provide enough examples for the model to learn from, which could lead to poor performance
  • Longer sequences: With shorter sequences as provided in the dataset, the model may fail to capture adequate context as it has less information to learn from, which can lead to underfitting (which is likey as seen by the learning curves)
